  "summary": "Detective Constable Demot Craddock meets with photographer Margaret Bens to discuss the murder of Marina Gregg. Craddock explains that the county police commissioner transferred the case to him because it is considered a transatlantic matter. Margaret drives Craddock back to her studio on Tottenham Court Road to conduct their discussion.\n\nMargaret explains that she was hired to take exclusive photographs of a reception hosted by Marina Gregg and Jason Rad. She had positioned her camera on the stairs to capture guests ascending, which allowed her to see Marina clearly and occasionally see Jason Rad. However, she did not see Mrs. Bardwell and did not witness her drinking the fatal beverage. Margaret recalls photographing the mayor and notes that Adwick Fenn and Lola Brouste were walking up the stairs behind the mayor.\n\nWhen Craddock asks if Marina appeared uncomfortable or displayed an unusual expression, Margaret produces a glossy photograph she took of the victim. In the image, Marina is being held by a woman whose back is to the camera, but Marina’s eyes are fixed on something to the left with a completely expressionless face, showing neither fear nor pain. Craddock concludes that Marina had seen something significant. Margaret reveals she has not sold the photo to newspapers because she finds it unethical to profit from peering into someone's mind. Craddock notes that Margaret is straightforward, observing that she was trained in America.",
